---
layout: base
title: Volunteer with us
description: Open volunteer roles at The Umami Post. Recipe testing, editing, photography, code, and more.
permalink: /volunteer/
---

{% set positions = [
  {
    slug: "recipe-tester",
    title: "Recipe tester",
    commitment: "2-6 hrs / month",
    remote: "Fully remote (you cook in your own kitchen)",
    summary: "Cook a submitted recipe in your own kitchen, in your own equipment, with your own grocery store, and tell us what happened. The most important volunteer role on the site -- contributor recipes do not publish until at least one other cook has made them.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Pick up an assigned recipe and shop for it as a normal home cook would.",
      "Cook the recipe exactly as written, taking notes on anything ambiguous, anything that took longer or shorter than stated, anything that came out differently than the contributor described.",
      "Photograph at least the finished dish (a phone photo is fine).",
      "File a one-page test note: what worked, what failed, what you would change, whether you would make it again."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "You cook regularly at home -- you do not need to be a professional.",
      "You are willing to follow a recipe as written before you start improvising.",
      "You can be honest with a contributor about what did not work."
    ],
    apply: "Email a one-paragraph note about the kind of cooking you do most often and any dietary focus."
  },
  {
    slug: "copy-editor",
    title: "Copy editor",
    commitment: "3-6 hrs / week",
    remote: "Fully remote",
    summary: "Tighten prose, catch typos, enforce house style. The piece has been through a substantive edit; you are the last set of eyes before it ships.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Read each assigned piece for grammar, punctuation, agreement, and consistency.",
      "Flag tonal lapses (jargon, hedge-stacking, cooking-show breathlessness) without rewriting voice.",
      "Apply our house style: AP-derived with overrides for serial commas, em-dash spacing, ingredient amounts, and Latin abbreviations.",
      "Check headlines, deks, captions, ingredient lists, and step numbers -- these are where late errors usually hide.",
      "Suggest cuts when a paragraph could be tighter; the writer decides."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Demonstrable copy-editing experience or the equivalent obsessive reading habit.",
      "Comfortable with Markdown and Git (or willing to learn -- we pair-edit through the first three pieces).",
      "Patience for serial-comma debates."
    ],
    apply: "Email a sample of a piece you have copy-edited, before and after."
  },
  {
    slug: "photographer",
    title: "Photographer",
    commitment: "Per-recipe, 1-3 hrs",
    remote: "Fully remote (your kitchen)",
    summary: "Shoot photography for submitted recipes that arrive without it. Hero shot, ideally a step photo or two for the instruction column.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Pick up an assigned recipe that needs photography.",
      "Cook it (or coordinate with a recipe tester who is cooking it) and photograph the finished dish at minimum.",
      "Shoot a step photo or two if the recipe has a technique-heavy moment.",
      "Deliver photos in our requested formats (4:3 hero, 1:1 thumbnail) at sensible resolutions.",
      "Caption each photo briefly."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "A working camera (DSLR, mirrorless, or a good phone).",
      "Comfortable with food styling on a small scale -- nothing fussy, just respectable.",
      "Portfolio or representative samples we can look at."
    ],
    apply: "Email a portfolio link and the kind of cooking you most enjoy photographing."
  },
  {
    slug: "translator",
    title: "Translator",
    commitment: "Per-piece, 2-6 hrs",
    remote: "Fully remote",
    summary: "Translate recipes and articles into other languages so coverage of food culture and technique is not trapped in English. Translations publish under the original author's byline plus a translator credit.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Translate full recipes or articles from English into your target language, preserving voice and cadence rather than producing literal word-for-word.",
      "Convert measurements to the conventions of your target audience (metric, imperial, or both).",
      "Flag idioms and culture-specific references that need translator notes.",
      "Add a brief translator's note at the end of any piece that required adaptation choices worth surfacing."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Native or near-native fluency in target language; fluent in English.",
      "A piece of published translation we can read, even informal.",
      "Bonus: familiarity with the cuisine or food culture you are translating into."
    ],
    apply: "Email naming your target language(s) and including one translation sample (any genre)."
  },
  {
    slug: "events-coordinator",
    title: "Events coordinator",
    commitment: "Variable; bursts around quarterly events",
    remote: "Hybrid (remote planning, occasional in-person)",
    summary: "Plan and run reader events -- supper clubs, technique workshops, cookbook launches, recipe-testing meetups. We do not yet have a formal events programme; you would help build one.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Propose 1-2 events per quarter (topic, format, target audience).",
      "Coordinate venue, scheduling, RSVPs, and any speaker / chef logistics.",
      "Wire the events into the site's events calendar and into the newsletter.",
      "Handle live moderation or hand off cleanly to whoever is moderating.",
      "Write a brief post-event note for the publication's archive."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Has run at least one public-facing event before, even informally.",
      "Comfortable being the person who confirms the venue, sends the reminders, and answers the day-of-questions.",
      "If hybrid: based in or able to travel to a major US metro."
    ],
    apply: "Email pitching the first event you would want to run."
  },
  {
    slug: "community-moderator",
    title: "Community moderator",
    commitment: "1-3 hrs / week",
    remote: "Fully remote",
    summary: "Read the comment threads, the webmention inbox, and the tip line. Surface what deserves an editorial response, hide what doesn't, escalate harassment.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Triage daily / weekly comment + webmention activity. Approve, hide, or flag.",
      "Apply the community guidelines fairly and consistently.",
      "Surface comments worth responding to or promoting into a Cook's Letter.",
      "Escalate harassment, doxxing attempts, or coordinated review-bombing to the editor.",
      "Maintain the blocklist when it grows."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Calm under provocation. Public-internet veteran.",
      "Read the community guidelines and agreed with the substance.",
      "No active fights with subjects of our coverage; conflicts of interest disqualify."
    ],
    apply: "Email describing your prior moderation experience and one ambiguous comment thread you would handle and why."
  },
  {
    slug: "newsletter-curator",
    title: "Newsletter curator",
    commitment: "1-2 hrs / week",
    remote: "Fully remote",
    summary: "Build the weekly newsletter from the published archive. Choose what gets featured, write the connecting prose, send through Buttondown.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Read the week's published recipes and stories and select 4-8 for the newsletter.",
      "Write a 2-3 sentence editor's note for the top of the issue.",
      "Pull cover image, dek, and lead sentence for each featured piece.",
      "Send via Buttondown on the same day each week and watch for delivery issues.",
      "Maintain a small evergreen file of pieces to re-feature on slow weeks."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Strong instinct for which piece earns the lead spot in a given week.",
      "Comfortable with Markdown and a newsletter sending tool (Buttondown is what we use).",
      "Reliable delivery cadence."
    ],
    apply: "Email a sample issue you would send this week, drawn from our recent archive."
  },
  {
    slug: "developer",
    title: "Developer / open-source contributor",
    commitment: "Issue-by-issue",
    remote: "Fully remote",
    summary: "Help build the publication's underlying static-site stack. The whole codebase is on GitHub; we accept issues and PRs from anyone.",
    responsibilities: [
      "Pick up open issues on the-umami-post repo.",
      "Submit PRs with tests and clear commit messages.",
      "Review other contributors' PRs.",
      "Improve docs as you go -- the README, CONTRIBUTING, and EDITORIAL guides are all in-repo."
    ],
    qualifications: [
      "Familiar with Eleventy, Nunjucks, plain CSS, or willing to come up to speed.",
      "Public GitHub history we can read.",
      "Bonus: accessibility work, performance work, or design-system experience."
    ],
    apply: "Open a PR or an issue on the the-umami-post repo with your name on it; we will find you."
  }
] %}

<div class="container" style="padding-top: var(--space-10); padding-bottom: var(--space-20);">

  <header class="page-header">
    <p class="page-header__eyebrow">Volunteer</p>
    <h1 class="page-header__title">Help build {{ site.title }}</h1>
    <p class="page-header__lede">
      {{ site.title }} is a small, independent food publication. Volunteers fill the roles a fully-funded magazine would pay for. The publication does not currently pay contributors a salary -- volunteer work is contribution, not employment, and we are explicit about that up front. <a href="/license/">Republication terms</a>, <a href="/ethics/">editorial ethics</a>, <a href="/transparency/">how we operate</a>.
    </p>
  </header>

  <div class="sg-layout">

    <aside class="sg-nav" aria-label="Open positions">
      {% for p in positions %}
      <a href="#{{ p.slug }}">{{ p.title }}</a>
      {% endfor %}
      <a href="#general">General volunteer interest</a>
    </aside>

    <div class="article-body">

      <p>Each role below has a written brief: what you would do, the rough time commitment, what we look for, and how to apply. Read the one that fits and email us per the apply note. If nothing fits but you want to help, jump to the <a href="#general">general volunteer interest</a> form at the bottom.</p>

      {% for p in positions %}
      <section id="{{ p.slug }}" class="volunteer-position">
        <header class="volunteer-position__head">
          <h2 class="volunteer-position__title">{{ p.title }}</h2>
          <p class="volunteer-position__meta">
            <span>{{ p.commitment }}</span>
            <span>{{ p.remote }}</span>
          </p>
        </header>

        <p class="volunteer-position__summary">{{ p.summary }}</p>

        <h3>Responsibilities</h3>
        <ul>
          {% for r in p.responsibilities %}<li>{{ r }}</li>{% endfor %}
        </ul>

        <h3>What we look for</h3>
        <ul>
          {% for q in p.qualifications %}<li>{{ q }}</li>{% endfor %}
        </ul>

        <h3>How to apply</h3>
        <p>{{ p.apply }} Send to <a href="mailto:{{ site.email }}?subject=Volunteer%20application%20--%20{{ p.title | urlencode }}">{{ site.email }}</a> with the role name in the subject line.</p>
      </section>
      {% endfor %}

      <section id="general" class="volunteer-position">
        <header class="volunteer-position__head">
          <h2 class="volunteer-position__title">General volunteer interest</h2>
          <p class="volunteer-position__meta"><span>Open</span><span>No commitment yet</span></p>
        </header>

        <p>Want to help but don't see the right slot above? Tell us what you would want to do and what time you have. We read every note. If we have something that fits, we will write back; if we do not, we will say so cleanly.</p>

        <form action="https://api.web3forms.com/submit" method="POST" class="w3f">
          <input type="hidden" name="access_key" value="{{ site.forms.accessKey }}">
          <input type="hidden" name="subject" value="Volunteer interest, {{ site.title }}">
          <input type="hidden" name="redirect" value="{{ site.url }}/thank-you/">
          <input type="hidden" name="from_name" value="{{ site.title }} Volunteer Form">
          <input type="checkbox" name="botcheck" class="visually-hidden" style="display:none" tabindex="-1" autocomplete="off">

          <div class="w3f__row">
            <div class="w3f__group">
              <label class="w3f__label" for="vol-name">Name <span class="w3f__required">*</span></label>
              <input class="w3f__input" type="text" name="name" id="vol-name" required aria-required="true" autocomplete="name">
            </div>
            <div class="w3f__group">
              <label class="w3f__label" for="vol-email">Email <span class="w3f__required">*</span></label>
              <input class="w3f__input" type="email" name="email" id="vol-email" required aria-required="true" autocomplete="email">
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="w3f__group">
            <label class="w3f__label" for="vol-interest">Which role(s) interest you?</label>
            <select class="w3f__select" name="role_interest" id="vol-interest">
              <option value="">Select one</option>
              {% for p in positions %}<option value="{{ p.title }}">{{ p.title }}</option>{% endfor %}
              <option value="Other / not sure yet">Other / not sure yet</option>
            </select>
          </div>

          <div class="w3f__group">
            <label class="w3f__label" for="vol-experience">Relevant experience <span class="w3f__required">*</span></label>
            <textarea class="w3f__textarea" name="experience" id="vol-experience" rows="5" required aria-required="true" maxlength="3000" placeholder="What have you done that is relevant to the role you picked? Links welcome."></textarea>
          </div>

          <div class="w3f__group">
            <label class="w3f__label" for="vol-time">Realistic time you can give</label>
            <input class="w3f__input" type="text" name="time_commitment" id="vol-time" placeholder="e.g. ~3 hrs/week, evenings UK time">
          </div>

          <div class="h-captcha" data-captcha="true"></div>
          <div class="w3f__status" role="status" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true"></div>
          <button type="submit" class="w3f__submit">Send</button>
          <p class="w3f__privacy">Delivered to our editorial inbox via Web3Forms. We never sell or share submissions. See our <a href="/privacy/#contact-forms">privacy policy</a>.</p>
        </form>

      </section>

    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<style>
.volunteer-position {
  margin-top: var(--space-10);
  padding-top: var(--space-6);
  border-top: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
}
.volunteer-position:first-of-type { margin-top: var(--space-6); border-top: 0; padding-top: 0; }
.volunteer-position__head { margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
.volunteer-position__title {
  font-family: var(--font-headline);
  font-size: var(--text-xl);
  margin: 0 0 var(--space-2);
  scroll-margin-top: 6rem;
}
.volunteer-position__meta {
  font-family: var(--font-ui);
  font-size: var(--text-xs);
  font-weight: 700;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-ink-faint);
  margin: 0;
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  gap: var(--space-1) var(--space-4);
}
.volunteer-position__summary {
  font-family: var(--font-body);
  font-size: var(--text-md);
  color: var(--color-ink-muted);
  font-style: italic;
  line-height: var(--leading-normal);
  margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  max-width: 65ch;
}
</style>
